{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 \fmodern Courier;}}
{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 MIDI CC Compressor\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This .jsfx acts as a CC compressor and fattens up the CC curve, by increasing the input CC values.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Sample use case: Some guitar synths and MIDI guitar controllers send string envelope information via MIDI for each string. A CC event is often used; the value is based on the amplitude of the string over time. E.g., the Jamstik in MPE mode defaults to using CC11 on channels 2-7 to represent the string level for each of the 6 guitar strings. This CC can be used to drive a parameter in your synth, e.g., a filter or volume. It's basically an old-school envelope follower. Since it follows the string's natural decay, however, there is a fairly rapid dropoff of the value after the initial attack. This .jsfx slows down that decay and fattens up the CC tail. This can provide more sustain and a more full sound, e.g., when used to drive synth volume for that channel/part.\par}
}

